{
  "texts": [
    "Named entity recognition (NER) is a fundamental task in natural language processing that aims to identify entity mentions in input text and assign them to specific types (Mikheev et al., 1999; Lample et al., 2016).",
    "Previous works solve NER tasks by training models on human-annotated datasets (Kim et al., 2003; Li et al., 2016; Zhang et al., 2021), improving neural model architectures (Jeong and Kang, 2023), or leveraging external knowledge (Liu et al., 2019; Mengge et al., The definition describes \"NF-kappa B\" as... which implies it is a type of protein involved in gene regulation.",
    "Also the semantic type provided,... further supports that NF-kappa B belongs to the protein category. 2020; Wang et al., 2021).",
    "More recently, simply prompting large language models (LLMs) without training can also perform NER tasks (Wang et al., 2023a; Ashok and Lipton, 2023).",
    "Despite the promising results of these approaches, they still produce plausible but imprecise outputs."
  ]
}